","about 1132":"circa 1132","1170":"1170","Hulme, Lancashire, England":"Hulme, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"about 1132–":"about 1132–Deceased","1130–1170":"1130–1170","1154–1205":"1154–1205","1132–Female":"1132–Deceased","about 1150":"about 1150","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1154":"1154","1132":"1132","1130":"1130","about 1132":"about 1132","1170":"1170","Hulme, Lancashire, England":"Hulme, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Davenport","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cheshire): habitational name from a place in Cheshire named Davenport, from the Dane river (apparently named with a Celtic cognate of Middle Welsh <i>dafnu</i> ‘to drop, to trickle’) + Old English <i>port</i> ‘market town’.","Irish: in Tipperary, this is an English surname adopted by bearers of Munster Gaelic <b>Ó Donndubhartaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Donndubhartach</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>donn</i> ‘brown-haired man’ or ‘chieftain’ + <i>dubh</i> ‘black’ + <i>artach</i> ‘nobleman’.","History: John Davenport (died 1670) arrived in Boston, MA, in 1637. He came of an English Cheshire family associated with Capesthorne Hall, near Macclesfield."],"variants":[{"name":"Devenport","meanings":["English and Irish (Lancashire): variant of   Davenport  . The spelling <b>Devonport</b> is found in Ireland and it may have been this form which gave rise to <i>Devenport</i>."]},{"name":"Dunworth","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Eamon, Niall.","Irish: adopted in Ireland by bearers of Gaelic <b>Ó Donndubhartaigh</b> (see   Davenport   2).","English: perhaps a variant of <b>Dungworth</b>, see   Dunsworth  ."]}]},{"name":"Ormus","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dutch: nickname from the Christian liturgic Latin phrase <i>oremus</i> ‘let us pray’, probably applied to someone who used this phrase in difficult situations. As a noun <i>oremus</i> became a metaphor for troubles.","Croatian (<b>Oremuš</b>): from the personal name <i>Oremuš</i>, regional vernacular form of Latin   Hieronymus  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hieronymus","meanings":["form of Greek <i>Hieronymos</i> (  see  <b>Jerome</b>   ), still used in Germany, especially in Catholic Bavaria and the Rhineland."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":83,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":92,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Ormus Davenport was born about 1132, in Hulme, Lancashire, England. She married John Hulme about 1150, in Hulme, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1132–":"umbes 1132–Surnud","1130–1170":"1130–1170","1154–1205":"1154–1205","1132–Female":"1132–Surnud","about 1150":"umbes 1150","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1154":"1154","1132":"1132","1130":"1130","about 1132":"umbes 1132","1170":"1170","Hulme, Lancashire, England":"Hulme, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"about 1132–":"noin 1132–Kuollut","1130–1170":"1130–1170","1154–1205":"1154–1205","1132–Female":"1132–Kuollut","about 1150":"noin 1150","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1154":"1154","1132":"1132","1130":"1130","about 1132":"noin 1132","1170":"1170","Hulme